Everybody called her Aspirin -- she always looked like she was aspiring to become a special state of being, and just looking at her made your headache go away.

It wasn't that she was classically beautiful, though she possessed a certain symmetry that pleased the eye. It was something more atmospheric. She moved through the crowded hallways of Jefferson High with the buoyancy of a helium balloon, untethered from the petty grievances and gravitational pull of teenage drama. While the rest of us were bogged down by the weight of grades, popularity, and the crushing awkwardness of puberty, Aspirin floated.

Her real name was Alice Pemberton, a name that felt too heavy, too starched and formal for someone so ethereal. "Alice" sounded like the name of a girl who sat in the front row and reminded the teacher about homework. Aspirin, however, fit her perfectly. It was a moniker born of relief.

I remember the day the nickname stuck. It was mid-November, a gray, drizzling Tuesday that matched the collective mood of the sophomore class. We were trapped in Mr. Henderson’s history class, the air thick with the smell of wet wool and the drone of a lecture on the Teapot Dome Scandal. My head was pounding—a stress migraine that had been building since first period. Then, Alice walked in. She was late, holding a hall pass that fluttered in her hand like a wounded bird. She didn't scurry or slink; she drifted to her seat by the window. As she passed my desk, she smiled—a small, distracted curve of the lips—and the throbbing behind my eyes simply... evaporated.

"Wow," whispered Marcus from the row behind me. "My headache's gone."

"Mine too," I murmured, rubbing my temples in disbelief.

Marcus leaned forward. "She’s like walking medicine. She’s... Aspirin."

The name spread through the school faster than the flu. But unlike the flu, Aspirin was a cure, not a contagion. People began to seek her out, not for conversation or dates, but for proximity. During lunch, she would sit on the bleachers in the gym, eating a sandwich and staring at the dust motes dancing in the light of the high windows. Slowly, a perimeter would form around her. The stressed, the heartbroken, the anxious—they would gravitate toward her bench, sitting in a silent, reverent circle. Nobody spoke to her much; we just breathed the same air. It was a strange, cult-like devotion, born not of worship, but of desperate need for relief.

But there was a tragedy to Aspirin that we were all too selfish to see at the time. We treated her like a pill to be swallowed, a balm for our own friction burns. We never stopped to ask what it cost her to be so buoyant, or what she was actually aspiring to.

I found out one evening in the library, weeks before graduation. I was shelving books for a work-study shift, and I found her in the back corner, tucked behind the biographies. She wasn't floating then. She was sitting on the floor with her knees pulled to her chest, looking heavy and grounded. The air around her felt dense, suffocating.

I froze. I had a headache from the fluorescent lights, and instinctively, I took a step toward her, expecting the usual relief. But as I got closer, the pain sharpened. It was as if she was absorbing the comfort out of the room, pulling it into herself to maintain her own equilibrium.

She looked up, her eyes red-rimmed and tired. "Go away, Jeremy," she said softly. Her voice didn't sound like wind chimes anymore; it sounded like gravel.

"I just... I have a headache," I stammered, feeling like a junkie looking for a fix.

She laughed, a dry, humorless sound. "Of course you do. You all do."

She stood up, brushing off her skirt, and the motion seemed to cost her immense effort. "You know why they call me Aspirin, Jeremy? Because I take on the pain. I absorb it. I take your headaches, your heartbreak, your crushing boredom, and I hold it so you don't have to. That’s the 'special state of being' I’m aspiring to. I’m trying to hold it all together so I don't explode."

I stared at her, the realization washing over me with the cold clarity of ice water. She wasn't floating because she was lighter than air; she was floating because she was trying to keep her head above a rising tide of everyone else's misery.

"I'm sorry," I said, the words feeling inadequate.

"Don't be sorry," she said, her shoulders squaring, the mask of serenity sliding back into place. I watched as she took a deep breath, and I saw the physical shift—the tightening of her jaw, the brightening of her eyes. She was pulling the weight back onto herself. Instantly, the pressure in my temples vanished.

She smiled at me, that same distracted, beatific smile. "Feel better?"

I nodded, unable to speak.

"Good," she said, turning to leave. "I have to go. Marcus is having a panic attack over his college applications, and Sarah just got dumped. Everyone needs their fix."

She walked out of the library, moving with that familiar, effortless grace. She looked like she was aspiring to become something divine, something untouched by the world. But as I watched her go, I realized the truth. Aspirin didn't make the headache go away; she just took it with her. And as she drifted down the hallway, carrying the weight of a hundred small sufferings, I wondered how much more she could hold before she finally sank. [end of text]


